 <exercise xml:id="Planes20">
    <statement>
    <p>
      Find an equation for the plane that contains both of the lines described in <xref ref="Ez_9_5_2"/>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) = 0</m> or <m>2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) = 0</m> or <m>2x + 4y = 0</m>.
    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Find the normal vector to the two direction vectors. <m>\vu \times \vv = ((1)(5) - (3)(1))\vi - ((-2)(5) - (3)(-2))\vj + ((-2)(1) - (-2)(1))\vk = \langle 2, 4, 0 \rangle</m>. Use either <m>(4, -2, 1)</m> or <m>(-4, 2, 17)</m> and <m>\langle 2, 4, 0 \rangle</m> to write the scalar equation of the plane <m>2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) + 0(z - 17) = 2(x + 4) + 4(y - 2) = 0</m> or <m>2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) + 0(z - 1) = 2(x - 4) + 4(y + 2) = 0</m>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_3">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This exercise explores key relationships between a pair of planes. Consider the following two planes: one with scalar equation <m>4x - 5y + z = -2</m>, and the other which passes through the points <m>(1,1,1)</m>, <m>(0,1,-1)</m>, and <m>(4, 2, -1)</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a vector normal to the first plane.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vn = \langle 4, -5, 1 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The coefficients in front of the variables identify the normal vector <m>\vn = \langle 4, -5, 1 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a scalar equation for the second plane.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>2(x - 1) - 8(y - 1) - (z - 1) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The vector from <m>(1, 1, 1)</m> to <m>(0, 1, -1)</m> is <m>\langle -1, 0, -2 \rangle</m>. The vector from <m>(1, 1, 1)</m> to <m>(4, 2, -1)</m> is <m>\langle 3, 1, -2 \rangle</m>. 
          </p>
          <p>
            The cross product of the vectors is <m>((0)(-2) - (-2)(1))\vi - ((-1)(-2) - (-2)(3))\vj + ((-1)(1) - (0)(3))\vk = \langle 2, -8, -1 \rangle</m>. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Therefore, the equation of the line is <m>2(x - 1) - 8(y - 1) - (z - 1) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the angle between the planes, where the angle between them is defined by the angle between their respective normal vectors.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>29.18^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Find the angle between the normal vectors. <m>\theta = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\vu\cdot\vv}{\vecmag{\vu}\vecmag{\vv}}\right) = \cos^{-1}\left(\frac{(4)(2) + (-5)(-8) + (1)(-1)}{\sqrt{42} \sqrt{69}}\right) = 29.18^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a point that lies on both planes.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>(0, \frac{9}{13}, -\frac{-19}{13})</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Rewrite the scalar equation from <m>b.</m> as <m>2x - 2 - 8y + 8 -z + 1 = 2x - 8y -z + 7 = 0</m>. Rewrite as <m>2x - 8y -z = -7</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We have a system of 2 equations with 3 variables. If we add the equations, we get <m>6x - 13y = -9</m>. Choose an <m>x</m>-value and solve for <m>y</m>. Let <m>x = 0</m>. Then <m>y = \frac{9}{13}</m>. Plug these values into either equation then solve for <m>z</m> to get <m>z = -\frac{19}{13}</m>. This point is <m>(0, \frac{9}{13}, -\frac{-19}{13})</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Since these two planes do not have parallel normal vectors, the planes must intersect, and thus must intersect in a line.  Observe that the line of intersection lies in both planes, and thus the direction vector of the line must be perpendicular to each of the respective normal vectors of the two planes.  Find a direction vector for the line of intersection for the two planes.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vn \times \vm = \langle 13, 6, -22 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Find the cross product of the normal vectors. <m>\langle 4, -5, 1 \rangle \times \langle 2, -8, -1 \rangle = \langle 13, 6, -22 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine parametric equations for the line of intersection of the two planes.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Answer depends on the point found in (d). <m>x(t) = 13t, y(t) = \frac{9}{13} + 6t, z(t) = -\frac{19}{13} - 22t</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Using the point found in (d) and the normal vector from (e), <m>x(t) = 13t, y(t) = \frac{9}{13} + 6t, z(t) = -\frac{19}{13} - 22t</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
  
    </exercise>

<exercise>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the plane that goes through the points <m>(1,2,3)</m>, <m>(4,5,6)</m>, and <m>(7,8,9)</m> or explain why there is not one plane that satisfies this condition.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        These three points are collinear, so there is not just one plane that goes through these points.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <em>all</em> planes in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> whose line of intersection with the <m>xz</m>-plane is given by <m>\pi x +e z=\sqrt{5}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Planes will be of the form <m>\pi x +By +e z=\sqrt{5}</m>, where <m>B</m> can be any real number.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give two vectors that are in the plane given by <m>3x+4y=6z-20</m> and are orthogonal to each other. 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        What geometric information do you have about vectors in the given plane?
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We need to pick two vectors that will be orthogonal to <m>\langle 3,4,-6\rangle </m> and to each other. First we can pick a vector orthogonal to <m>\langle 3,4,-6\rangle </m> in similar way to how we completed the Preview Activity. For example, <m>\langle 2,0,1\rangle </m> will be orthogonal to <m>\langle 3,4,-6\rangle </m>. To find a vector orthogonal to both <m>\langle 2,0,1\rangle </m> and <m>\langle 3,4,-6\rangle </m>, we can use the cross product, which gives  <m>\langle 2,0,1\rangle \times \langle 3,4,-6\rangle =\langle -4,15,8\rangle </m>. The vectors <m>\langle 2,0,1\rangle </m> and <m>\langle -4,15,8\rangle </m> will be orthogonal to each other and in the direction of the plane given by <m>3x+4y=6z-20</m>. There is not a unique solution to this problem. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give the equations of <em>two</em> planes that make a <m>90^\circ</m> angle with <m>3x+4y=6z-20</m> and have an angle of <m>90^\circ</m> between them as well.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We can use our solutions from the previous problem as normal vectors for our planes here. Because <m>\langle 2,0,1\rangle</m>, <m> \langle 3,4,-6\rangle </m>, and <m>\langle -4,15,8\rangle </m> are all orthogonal as vectors, then the planes with these as normal vectors will have perpendicular intersections. Using this idea, we can use planes of the form <m>2x+z=A</m> and <m>-4x+15y+8z=B</m> for any values of <m>A</m> or <m>B</m>. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give the parametric form of the line of intersection for the planes given by <m>x+y+z=10</m> and <m>-2x-4y+2z=7</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        To give the parametric form of a line for this intersection, we need to find a point on this line and the direction this line can go. The direction vector for this line will need to be orthogonal to the normal vectors of both planes. We can use the cross product of the normal vector to easily find a representative of this direction, <m> \langle 1,1,1 \rangle \times \langle -2,-4,2 \rangle = \langle 6,-4,-2 \rangle </m>. 
      </p>
      <p>
        We can find a point of intersection many different ways. For example, we can set <m>x=0</m> in both equations and solve for the appropriate y and z coordinates to get the point <m>(0,\frac{13}{6},\frac{47}{6})</m>. Combining this information, we get the parameterization <m>\vr(t) =\langle 0,\frac{13}{6},\frac{47}{6} \rangle + t \langle 6,-4,-2 \rangle </m>. Remember that this parameterization is not unique and may be given with a different point on the line or a parallel direction vector. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

