<exercise label="Library__UMN__calculusStewartET__s_12_5_prob02.pg" xml:id="Planes19">
<!--<title></title>-->
    <webwork source="Library/UMN/calculusStewartET/s_12_5_prob02.pg"/>
</exercise> 



    
    <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_5_4">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          In this problem, we explore how we can use what we know about vectors and projections to find the distance from a point to a
          plane.
        </p>
        <p>
           Let <m>p</m> be the plane with equation <m>z=-4x+3y+4</m>, and let <m>Q = (4,-1,8)</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Show that <m>Q</m> does not lie in the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Plug in <m>x = 4</m> and <m>y = -1</m> to the given equation. The output is not equal to <m>8</m>, so <m>Q</m> does not lie in the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Plug in <m>x = 4</m> and <m>y = -1</m> to the given equation. <m>z = -4(4) + 3(-1) + 4 = -15</m> which is not equal to <m>8</m>. Therefore <m>Q</m> does not lie in the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a normal vector <m>\vn</m> to the plane <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vn = \langle -4, 3, -1 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The normal vector can be identified by looking at the coefficients of the variables in scalar form. <m>-4x + 3y -z + 4 = 0</m> has a normal vector of <m>\langle -4, 3, -1 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the coordinates of a point <m>P</m> in <m>p</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            A point in <m>p</m> is <m>(0, 0, 4)</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Choose any <m>x</m>-value and <m>y</m>-value. Then find the corresponding <m>z</m>-value. Let <m>x = 0, y = 0</m>, then <m>z = 4</m>. The point is <m>(0, 0, 4)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the components of <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m>. Draw a picture to illustrate the objects found so far.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = \langle 4, -1, 4 \rangle</m>. Then sketch a picture.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = \langle 4 - 0, -1 - 0, 8 - 4 \rangle = \langle 4, -1, 4 \rangle</m>. Then sketch a picture.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why <m>|\comp_{\vn} \overrightarrow{PQ}|</m> gives the distance from the point <m>Q</m> to the plane <m>p</m>. Find this distance.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Draw <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> with an initial point <m>P</m> in plane <m>p</m> and terminal point <m>Q</m> in a different plane that contains <m>Q</m>. Then construct a normal vector in plane <m>p</m>, from plane <m>p</m> to the point <m>Q</m>. The length of the projection of <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> onto the normal vector is <m>|\comp_{\vn} \overrightarrow{PQ}| = |-\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}| = \frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>. The distance from point <m>Q</m> to the plane <m>p</m> is <m>\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>. 
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Draw <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> with an initial point <m>P</m> in plane <m>p</m> and terminal point <m>Q</m> in a different plane that contains <m>Q</m>. Then construct a normal vector in plane <m>p</m>, from plane <m>p</m> to the point <m>Q</m>. The length of the projection of <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> onto the normal vector is <m>|\comp_{\vn} \overrightarrow{PQ}| = |-\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}| = \frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>. This means the distance from point <m>Q</m> to the plane <m>p</m> is <m>\frac{23}{\sqrt{26}}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>



</exercises>
